number of miles from the Sebou is the town of Sallee‚ situated on the river of the same name; this town is on the very edge of the desert, 'and is beset by herds of elephants, but much more seriously harried by the Autololes tribe, through whose terri- tory lies the road to Mount Atlas, which is the sub- ject of much the most marvellous stories of all the mountains in Africa. It is reported to rise into the sky out of the middle of the sands, a rugged eminence covered with crags on the side facing towards the coast of the Ocean to which it has given its name, but shaded by dense woods and watered by gushing springs on the side facing Africa, where sruits of all kinds spring up of their own accord with such luxuriance that pleasure never lacks satisfaction. It is said that in the day-time none of its inhabitants are seen, and that all is silent with a terrifying silence like that of the desert, so that a speechless awe creeps into the hear-ts of those who approach it, and also a dread of the peak that soars above the clouds and reaches the neighbourhood of the moon’s orb; also that at night this peak flashes with frequent sires and swarms with the wanton gambols of Goat-Pans and Satyrs, and eehoes with the music of flutes and pipes and the sound of drums and cymbals. These stories have been published by celebrated authors, in addition to the labours per- formed in this region by Hercules and Perseus. It is an immense distance away, across unexplored country.
